Theoretical Exercises

P.1 (10 points) For $A \in \R^{n x n}$ to be real positive semi-definite, it needs to satisfy for any $x \in \R^{n}$, $x^{T}Ax \geqslant 0$. Construct an example showing that $A$ need not be symmetric but can be real positive semi-definite. (You may look at the smaller $n$ case.)

     Proof:

Suppose there a matrix $A \in \R^{2 x 2}$, which is defined as,

$$\begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} \\\ a_{21} & a_{22} \end{pmatrix}.$$

Then suppose there existed a vector, $x \in \R^{2}$, which is defined as,

$$\begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}.$$

Calculating the inner prodict of $A$ and $x$, we attain,

$$x^{T}Ax=\begin{pmatrix} x_{1} & x_{2} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}= \begin{pmatrix} x_{1}a_{11}+x_{2}a_{21} & x_{1}a_{12}+x_{2}a_{22} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}$$

$$= x_{1}^{2}a_{11}+x_{1}x_{2}a_{21}+x_{1}x_{2}a_{12}+x_{2}^{2}a_{22}=x_{1}^{2}a_{11}+x_{1}x_{2} \begin{pmatrix}a_{21}+a_{12} \end{pmatrix} +x_{2}^{2}a_{22}.$$

Case (i): Consequentially for matrix $A$ to be at least positive semi-definite, $a_{21}+a_{12}=0$, so if we constructed a matrix with this condition satisfied, said matrix would be at least positive semi-definite.

Case (ii): when $a_{21}+a_{12}\ne 0$, such as when $a_{21}=0$ and $a_{12}=\pm 2$ and $a_{11}$, $a_{22}=1$, then we get,

$$x^{T}Ax=\begin{pmatrix} x_{1} & x_{2} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}1 & \pm 2 \\ 0 & 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}= \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} & \pm 2 x_{1}+x_{2} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}$$

$$= x_{1}^{2} \pm 2 x_{1}x_{2}+x_{2}^{2}= \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \pm x_{2} \end{pmatrix}^{2} \geqslant 0.$$

If the matrix forms a perfect square, then said matrix is said to be at least positive semi-definite. $\square$

P.2 (10 points) For $A \in \R^{n x n}$ to be real positive definite, it needs to satisfy for any non-zero $x \in \R^{n x n}$, $x^{T}Ax > 0$. Construct an example showing that $A$ need not be symmetric but can be real definite. (You may look at the smaller $n$ case.)

     Proof:

Suppose there a matrix $A \in \R^{2 x 2}$, which is defined as,

$$\begin{pmatrix} 2 & \pm 2 \\\ 0 & 2 \end{pmatrix}.$$

Then suppose there existed a vector, $x \in \R^{2}$, which is defined as,

$$\begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}.$$

Calculating the inner product of $A$ and $x$, we get,

$$x^{T}Ax=\begin{pmatrix} x_{1} & x_{2} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}2 & \pm 2 \\ 0 & 2 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 2x_{1} & 2x_{1} \pm 2x_{2} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} x_{1} \\\ x_{2} \end{pmatrix}$$

$$= 2x_{1}^{2}+2x_{1}x_{2}+2x_{2}^{2} = x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+(x_{1}+x_{2})^{2} > 0.$$

The inner product is greater than zero, and therefore matrix $A$ is positive definite. $\square$

P.1 (10 points) For $A \in \C^{n x n}$ to be positive definite, it needs to satisfy for any non-zero $x \in \C^{n}$, $x^{H}Ax > 0$. Prove that when $A$ is positive definite, it must be hermitian, i.e., $A^{H}=A$.

     Solution:

Suppose $A=A^{*}$ is a true statment, then since, $x^{*}Ax \in \R$, we also have $x^{*}Ax=x^{*}A^{*}x$,

$$x^{*}Ax=x^{*}A^{*}x \to x^{*}Ax-x^{*}A^{*}x=0 \to x^{*} \begin{pmatrix} Ax - A^{*}x \end{pmatrix} = 0 \to x^{*} \begin{pmatrix} Ax- A^{*} \end{pmatrix}x = 0,$$

for $\forall x \in \C^{n}$. Suppose that we choose a special eigenvector, $x$, such that $\begin{pmatrix} \lambda, x \end{pmatrix}$ becomes an eigen-pair of matrix $\begin{pmatrix} Ax- A^{*} \end{pmatrix}$, then we can attain,

$$Ax=\lambda x \to \begin{pmatrix} A-A^{*}\end{pmatrix} x=\lambda x \to x^{*} \begin{pmatrix} A-A^{*}\end{pmatrix} x= \lambda x^{*} x = 0.$$

Recollect that $x^{x}x = \Vert x \Vert$, is the norm of the vector, $x$, and that the norm of a eigenvector is always $1$, since they are always a orthonormalized vector. Consequentially since $x^{*}x \ne 0$, that means $\lambda = 0$, which means that all the eigenvalues of $\begin{pmatrix} Ax- A^{*} \end{pmatrix}$ are all zero.

Furthermore, $\begin{pmatrix} Ax- A^{*} \end{pmatrix}$ is anti-hermitian, and therefore it is diagonalizable. So, $A - A^{*} = QDQ^{*}$, where matrix $D$ is a diagonal zero matrix, which contains the zero eigenvalues. And therefore, $A - A^{*} = 0$, and so, $A = A^{*}$, which means that matrix $A$ is hermitian positive definite, e.g., HPD. $\square$

def sparse_coo(A):
    s=A.shape; n_rows=s[0]; n_cols=s[1];
    nnz=np.count_nonzero(A);
    AA=np.zeros(nnz); JR=np.zeros(nnz); JC=np.zeros(nnz);
    
    nnz_id=0;
    
    for i in range(n_rows):
        for j in range(n_cols):
            if A[i,j] != 0:
                JR[nnz_id]=i+1;
                JC[nnz_id]=j+1;
                AA[nnz_id]=A[i,j];
                nnz_id=nnz_id+1;
                
    print("AA = ")
    print(AA)
    print(" ")
    print("JR = ")
    print(JR)
    print(" ")
    print("JC = ")
    print(JC)
    
    return AA,JR,JC;

     On to the core of the scheme, we created a nested $\text{for}$ loop to sweep through each element of matrix $\text{A}$, and so to scrap the first nonzero element from each row of the matrix, we created a nested $\text{if}$ statement which stores the first value that it encouters, and then tests if it is the valid first nonzero element. By design this naive scrapping method is more computationlly expensive compared to industry implemented schemes, and thus further iteration to this scheme is needed to improve it computational overhead costs. Nevertheless to scrap the nonzero elements from matrix $\text{A}$, we used another $\text{if}$ statement which scrapped the nonzero elements and coordinate indices, and stored these values in $\text{AA}$ and $\text{JA}$, respectively. def sparse_csr(A):
    s=A.shape; n_rows=s[0]; n_cols=s[1];
    nnz=np.count_nonzero(A);
    AA=np.zeros(nnz); JA=np.zeros(nnz); IA=np.zeros(n_rows+1);
    
    nnz_id=0;
    id=0;
    
    for i in range(n_rows):
        id=0;
        for j in range(n_cols):
            if id==0:
                IA[i]=A[i,j];
                id=id+1;
                if IA[i]==0:
                    id=id-1;
            
            if A[i,j] != 0:
                JA[nnz_id]=j+1;
                AA[nnz_id]=A[i,j];
                nnz_id=nnz_id+1;
                
    IA[n_rows]=1+nnz;
    
    print("AA = ")
    print(AA)
    print(" ")
    print("JA = ")
    print(JA)
    print(" ")
    print("IA = ")
    print(IA)
    
    return AA,JA,IA;

     Our second aim is to devise two scheme to abridge the conversion between COO and CSR, so that we can converse between each format on a whim - depending on nessecity. To embark on we require the row dimensions of the full-matrix, which we are able to recover the row dimension of the full-matrix from lenght of $IA$ vector minus one, because this particular vector contains the first nonzero element in each row, and thus is an implied row indice of the full-matrix $\text{A}$. Following we had to change the single floating point precision format of $\text{m}$, $\text{JA}$, $\text{IA}$ to integer format, we did so to comform the Python's convention of integer indice-ization which is used in $\text{for}$ loop iteration, and so to adjust to rounding-point error in boolean statements that produce false - negatives or positives, when evaluating the validity of floating-point formatted values compared to integer formated values.

     In abridging CSR to COO, we could have modified the indices of CSR to COO, which could have significantly reduced the computationaly complexity of the abridgement process, but due our desire to experiment, we decide to pursue the more complicated scheme of recovering the full matrix, then passing on the recontructed matrix into $\text{sparse_coo}$ to complete the abridgement process. To do so we generated a zero matrix $\text{A}$ that would be used to recover the full-matrix structure through the following scheme sweeping through the zero matrix $\text{A}$ and inserting the nonzero elements in the correct coordinates. To do this, we had the outter $\text{for}$ loop iterate over the row dimensions of the full-matrix, and the inner $\text{for}$ loop iterate over the column dimensions of said matrix. We exploited the fact that $\text{JA}$ contained the column indices of the nonzero elements, we used an $\text{if}$ statement to insert the nonzero elements, and an iterative count denoted $\text{id}$ to iterate over $\text{JA}$. In otherwords, as the nested $\text{for}$ loop sweeps through the zero matrix $\text{A}$ the $\text{if}$ statement excutes for matching $\text{j}$ iterations with the $\text{JA[id]}$ column indices, e.g., $\text{j} = \text{JA[id]}$, which inserts the nonzero element into $\text{A[i,j]}$, which is denoted by the respective "current" iteration of the $\text{for}$ loop iteration. While the $\text{if}$ statement executes, and iter count $\text{id}$ iterates by one to denote an iteration over $\text{JA}$, which denotes the next nonzero element in $\text{AA}$.

     A fundamental flaw can occur when the iter count equals the lenght of nonzero elements in $\text{AA}$, e.g, $\text{id} = \text{nnz}$, which causes the $\text{if}$ statement to execute prematurely, causing it to insert the last element of the last row into the second to last row of the full-matrix; to correct for this flaw, we had to include an inner $\text{if}$ statement that forcely inserts a zero at $\text{A[n-1,m-1]}$ and de-iterates $\text{id}$ by one, which then allows for the last nonzero element to be inserted in $A[n,m]$. Anyhow with the reconstituted full-matrix $\text{A}$, we were able to pass on this full-matrix into $\text{sparse_coo()}$ to attain the COO format.

def csr2coo(AA,JA,IA,nnz):
    n=len(IA)-1; m=max(JA);
    m=m.astype(int); JA=JA.astype(int); IA=IA.astype(int);
    s=(n,m); JA_alt=JA-1;
    A=np.zeros(s); 
    
    nnz2=nnz;
    
    id=0;
    
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(m):
            if id==350:
                break;
            if JA_alt[id]==j:
                A[i,j]=AA[id];
                id=id+1;
                if id == nnz2:
                    if i !=n:
                        A[i,j]=0;
                        id=id-1;
                        nnz2=nnz2+1;
            elif JA[j]!=j:
                    A[i,j]=0;
                   
    
    [AA,JR,JC]=sparse_coo(A)
    
    return AA,JR,JC;

def coo2csr(AA,JR,JC):
    
    JA=JC; n_rows=max(JR); 
    n_rows=n_rows.astype(int); 
    JA=JA.astype(int); JR=JR.astype(int);
    nnz=len(AA);
    
    IA=np.zeros(n_rows+1);
    for i in range(nnz):
        IA[JR[i]]=IA[JR[i]]+1;
    for i in range(n_rows):
        IA[i+1]=IA[i+1]+IA[i];
        
    IA=IA+1;
    
    print("AA = ")
    print(AA)
    print(" ")
    print("JA = ")
    print(JA)
    print(" ")
    print("IA = ")
    print(IA)
    
    return AA,JA,IA;

     With that accomplished, we are able to devise a algorithm to perform matrix-vector multiplication, specifically, an algorihtm to perform matrix=vector multiplication with an CSR formatted matrix and a full-vector. To begin, we attained the row dimension of the compressed matrix with $\text{len(IA)-1}$ and stored the value in $\text{n}$, and attained the column dimension of the compressed matrix with $\text{max(JA)}$ and stored the values in $\text{m}$. And bacause of Python's integer format convention, we performed a series of $\text{astype(int)}$ type conversion from double floating point precision format to integer format. We then created a zero $\text{y}$ vector, a iter count $\text{id}$ and a dummy variable $\text{nnz2=nnz}$.

     Similar to $\text{csr2coo()}$ this algorithm sweeps through the matrix as $A[i,j:m]$ as $\text{n}=0,\ldots,n$, with an $\text{if}$ statement that only executes when $\text{JA_alt[id]==j}$, and thus executes a statement which multiplies $\text{AA[id]}$ with $x[j]$, which is the element-wise process of matrix-vector multiplication. Thus with this scheme we avoid zero-nonzero and zero-zero multiplications, while selecting for nonzero-nonzero multiplication to achieve a cost effective matrix-vector multication of a CSR matrix and a full-vector.

     In the same manner in $\text{coo2csr()}$, we implemented an similar inner $\text{if}$ statement to correct for the logical flaw that occurs when $\text{id}==\text{nnz2}$. In this case though we de-iterate $\text{id}$, so that we could remove the previous matrix-vector element from $\text{y[n-1]}$. And lastly we iterate $\text{nnz2}$ by one to make the $\text{if}$ statement false during the $i=n$ iteration.

def matvec_csr(AA,JA,IA,x):
    JA=JA.astype(int); IA=IA.astype(int); JA_alt=0; JA_alt=JA-1;
    n=len(IA)-1; m=max(JA); m=m.astype(int); nnz=len(AA);
    
    z=np.zeros((n,m));
    y=np.zeros(n);
    
    nnz2=nnz;
    
    id = 0;
    
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(m):
            if id==nnz:
                break;
            
            if JA_alt[id] == j:
                y[i]=y[i]+AA[id]*x[j];
                z[i,j]=AA[id]*x[j];
                id=id+1;
                if id == nnz2:
                    if i!=n:
                        id=id-1;
                        y[i]=y[i]-AA[id]*x[j];
                        nnz2=nnz2+1;
                    
    return y;

     Upon executation, one can discern that $\text{csr2coo()}$ was successful in convering compressed matrix $\text{A}$ from CSR format to COO format. Moreover the algorithm $\text{csr2coo()}$ was able to produce an result, but can we trust this result? We require a means to test this result, so we devised the following scheme to compare the result that Python would derive when conversing the compressed matrix $\text{A}$ from CSR format to COO format to our own algorithm's result, in doing testing the validity of our result.

     The first major setback was that $\text{numpy}$'s $\text{argwhere()}$ function does not return the the nonzero elements of the matrix like $\text{MATLAB}$'s $\text{find()}$ function, as a result we were not able to devise a scheme that would evaluate each of the nonzere element from the two results. Second major setback was that $\text{scipy}$ sparse matrices return as a proprietary data types (differn data types for each sparse format), which requires $\text{pandas}$ to convert into an $\text{numpy.array}$ data type, so to be able to interact with the resulting $\text{coo_matrix}$. Three major set back is the column and row indices are symobolically stored and require another method to physically scrap these values representing the indices of the nonzero elements into a seperate $\text{numpy.array}$, which can effectively act as an Python derived $\text{JR}/ \text{IA}$ and $\text{JC}/ \text{JA}$ vectors.

     Consequentially we devised the following scheme to compare the result of $\text{numpy}$'s $\text{argwhere()}$ function against our the result that was attained through our function, $\text{csr2coo()}$. The scheme follows a data analytic approach of deriving a boolean matrix of represent values of interest; of course, we will utlize this approach to not format or clean data, but to identify the correctness of $\text{JR}$ and $\text{JC}$ by producing a boolean array that represents the matching values between the two arrays.

     Also the block of Python code before the block of Python that contains the boolean vector test is to a block of code that temporarily blocks output to the console. I needed to re-execute $\text{sparse_coo()}$ to get a fresh execution in, as Jupyter notebook quircks, but I did not want the print statements to be printed here, so I include this clever block of code that I found from, Dave Smith's Blog.

from contextlib import contextmanager
import sys, os

@contextmanager
def suppress_stdout():
    with open(os.devnull, "w") as devnull:
        old_stdout = sys.stdout
        sys.stdout = devnull
        try:  
            yield
        finally:
            sys.stdout = old_stdout

     Once again we will borrow the example sparse matrix, $\text{A}$, from Example 3.7 of Saad (pg. 89, 2003) for the purpose of devising suitable algorithms to achieve our aims for this section of the project.

In [235]:
# create a sparse matrix
A=np.array([[1,0,0,2,0],[3,4,0,5,0],[6,0,7,8,9],[0,0,10,11,0],[0,0,0,0,12]]);

     In this section we are going to devise a scheme to compress matrix $\text{A}$ into the compressed sparse column (CSC) format. This CSC scheme is very similar in concept to CSR scheme we devised, first we defined the dimension parameters, $\text{n_rows}$, $\text{n_cols}$ for matrix $\text{A}$, and discerned quantity of nonzero elements in matrix $\text{A}$ and defined a object to store to value denote $\text{nnz}$. Similar to the CSR scheme, we generated three zero vectors, a zero vector named $\text{AA}$ of length $\text{nnz}$, and a zero vector named $\text{JR}$ of length $\text{nnz}$, and a zero vector named $\text{ptr}$ of lenght $\text{n_rows+1}$. Lastly we created two iter count objects, $\text{nnz_id}$ and $\text{id}$; the first to iterate over the compressed matrix vectors $\text{AA}$ and $\text{JR}$, and the second to keep tract of the first nonzero element in a column.

     Core of the CSC scheme is similar to the CSR scheme, though instead of scrapping the first nonzero columnm element in each row, we instead scrap the first nonzero row element in each column. Because of this change in iterative structure we switch the iterating indice from $A[i,j]$ to $A[j,i]$ to accommodate for the fact that scheme would be iterating over the row elements of each row, instead of iterating over the column elements in each row.

     To correct for an incorrect insertation into $\text{ptr}$, e.g, scheme inserting a zero element into $\text{ptr}$, we included an inner $\text{if}$ statement to test if the recently inserted element was zero or not, and if so, it would decrement the $\text{id}$, so that the outter $\text{if}$ statement could execute the next $\text{j}$ iteration. With this test in place, we are confident that the CSC scheme would contruct the correct $\text{ptr}$ vector for matrix $\text{A}$.

In [237]:
def sparse_csc(A):  
    s=A.shape; n_rows=s[0]; n_cols=s[1];
    nnz=np.count_nonzero(A);
    AA=np.zeros(nnz); JR=np.zeros(nnz); ptr=np.zeros(n_rows+1);
    
    nnz_id=0;
    id=0;
    
    for i in range(n_cols):
        id=0;
        for j in range(n_rows):
            if id==50:
                break
            if id==0:
                ptr[i]=A[j,i];
                id=id+1;
                if ptr[i]==0:
                    id=id-1;
            
            if A[j,i] != 0:
                JR[nnz_id]=j+1;
                AA[nnz_id]=A[j,i];
                nnz_id=nnz_id+1;
                
    ptr[n_rows]=1+nnz;
    
    print("AA = ")
    print(AA)
    print(" ")
    print("JR = ")
    print(JR)
    print(" ")
    print("ptr = ")
    print(ptr)
    
    return AA,JR,ptr;

     Upon testing $\text{sparse_csc()}$, we attained the expected corresponding compressed vectors for CSC format. With that concluded, we can proceed with the abridgement process of CSC format to COO format, and COO format to CSC format.

     The first abridgement scheme is $\text{csc2coo()}$, where the object is to transform the compress vectors of CSC format into COO format. To begin this process we attained the dimensions of each of the compress CSC vectors, and formatted each object's data type from double floating point precision format to integer format. As the scheme idea is to create the full matrix $\text{A}$ from the compressed CSC vectors, and therefore we generated a full matrix $\text{A}$ full of zeros.

     With the full-matrix $\text{A}$ full of zero element, we are able to sweep through this matrix, and insert the nonzero elements in the correct coordinates. An improvement upon $\text{csr2coo()}$, we constructed $\text{csc2coo()}$ to sweep the full matrix $\text{A}$ in reverse, so that we could implement an fail safe that incorporate the compressed vector $\text{ptr}$, which contains the first row element in each column of matrix $\text{A}$. This safe prevents the iter term, $\text{id}$ from over-iterating over$\text{AA}$, and thus preventing the scheme from inserting nonzero elements prematurely into $\text{A}$, and thus prevent the scheme from inserting these nonzero elements in the wrong coordinates.

     With matrix $\text{A}$ reconstituted, we were able to pass it through $\text{sparse_coo()}$ to attain the correct COO compressed vectors.

In [282]:
def csc2coo(AA,JR,ptr):
    m=len(ptr)-1; n=max(JR);
    n=n.astype(int); JR=JR.astype(int); 
    s=(n,m); JR_alt=JR-1; nnz=len(AA);
    A=np.zeros(s); 
    
    nnz2=nnz;

    id=nnz-1;

    for i in reversed(range(n)):
        for j in reversed(range(m)):
            if JR_alt[id]==j:
                A[j,i]=AA[id];
                id=id-1;
                if A[j,i]==ptr[i]:
                    break;
            elif JR[j]!=j:
                A[j,i]=0;
                          
    [AA,JR,JC]=sparse_coo(A)
    
    return AA,JR,JC;

     The next abridgement process is from COO format to CSC format, in the same fashion of $\text{csr2coo()}$ - we reconstruct the full-matrix $\text{A}$ with the compressed vectors - though this time with COO compressed vectors instead of CSR compressed vectors. Nevertheless I dare to speculate that the $\text{coo2csc()}$ scheme in reconsituting matrix $\text{A}$ is a bit more robust encomparison to $\text{csr2coo()}$, as the additional information provided allows for a simplier reconstruction process.

     We attained the dimensions of the COO compressed vectors, formatted the resulting objects appropriately, and generated an full-matrix $\text{A}$ full of zeros. The core of this abridgement scheme is sweep through the zero matrix $\text{A}$ and inserting nonzero element into their correct coordinates.

     Yet again a reconstituted matrix $\text{A}$, we were able to pass it through $\text{sparse_csc()}$ to attain the correct CSC compressed vectors.

def coo2csc(AA,JR,JC):
    m=max(JC); n=max(JR);
    m=m.astype(int); n=n.astype(int); 
    JR=JR.astype(int); JC=JC.astype(int); JC_alt=JC-1;
    s=(n,m); nnz=len(AA);
    A=np.zeros(s); 
    
    nnz2=nnz;
    
    id=0;
    
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(m):
            if JC_alt[id]==j:
                A[i,j]=AA[id];
                id=id+1;
                if id == nnz2:
                    A[i,j]=0;
                    id=id-1;
                    nnz2=nnz2+1;
            elif JC[j]!=j:
                A[i,j]=0;
                
    [AA,JR,ptr]=sparse_csc(A)
    
    return AA,JR,ptr;

def matvec_csc(AA,JR,ptr,x):
    m=len(ptr)-1; n=max(JR);
    n=n.astype(int); JR=JR.astype(int); 
    s=(n,m); JR_alt=JR-1; nnz=len(AA);
    A=np.zeros(s); 
    
    nnz2=nnz;

    id=nnz-1;

    for i in reversed(range(n)):
        for j in reversed(range(m)):
            if JR_alt[id]==j:
                A[j,i]=AA[id];
                id=id-1;
                if A[j,i]==ptr[i]:
                    break;
            elif JR[j]!=j:
                A[j,i]=0;
    
                    
    return y

C.3 (15 points) Implement the basic iterative methods, including the simple Richardson (M=I case), Jacobi, Gauss-Seidel (forward, backward, symmetric), and SOR (forward,backward,symmetric).

     Solution:

     With the development of an CSC format scheme and a CSC matrix-vector multiplication scheme, we can finally devote our effort towards the development of classical iterative methods. The first of these methods is the Richardson iterative method, a rather naive iterative method, but nevertheless a important method to cover in this section.

     The kernal of all classical iterative schemes is that they are all based around the concept cleaving of the matrix into paired matrices, denoted $\text{M}$ and $\text{N}$. In theory the cleaving of matrix $\text{A}$ into $\text{M}$ and $\text{N}$ subdivides the linear system and reduce the complexity of solving the linear system, so we get,

$$\text{M}x = \text{N}x^{0}+b.$$

     In this reduced system instead of attaining $\text{x}$ through solving matrix $A$, we attain $\text{X}$ from solving for $\text{M}$, which results in an computation which is significantly less computationally expensive than solvine for the full-system represented in matrix $\text{A}$.

     Given these points, Richardson iterative scheme is constructed by the simplest choice of matrix $\text{M}$ the identity matrix $\text{I}$ (Note: $\text{M}=\text{I}$).

$$Ax=b \to (M-N)x=b \to Mx=Nx+b \to Mx^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b$$

$$\to x^{(k+1)}=(I-A)x^{(k)}+b \to x^{(k+1)}= x^{(k)}+b-Ax^{k} \to x^{(k+1)}=x^{(k)}+r^{(k)}$$

A rather simple iterative scheme, the Richardson iterative scheme is quite naive, as the condition for convergence entirely depends upon the initial condition, $x_{0}$, which produces the null residual, $r_{0}$. If the initial condition is chosen well, then the subsequence residuals would approach machine epsilon, $\text{\epsilon}$, and the scheme would converge. Otherwise if the $x_{0}$ is chosen poorly Richardson iteration will diverge from the solution with successive residual measurements.

     The following block contains the code for a simple Richardson iteration scheme.

In [99]:
def Richardson_iter(A):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    I=np.identity(n);

    for i in range(iterMax):
        x=x+(b-np.linalg.solve((A),x));
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     Constructing a diagonally dominant matrix is not necessary to test the Richardson iteration scheme, but it will be necessary for the next iterative scheme, Jacobi, so we decide it best to construct a python function here to simply the examination process later.

In [100]:
def diagonally_dominant_matrix(n,m):
    a=n; b=m;
    
    A=np.random.random((a,b))
    A=np.abs(A);

    for i in range(n):
        A[i,i]=abs(sum(A[i,:])+10*A[i,i])
        
    return A;

     To test the Richardson iterative scheme, we chose to construct matrix $\text{A}$ as a strictly diagonally dominant matrix of size $n$ x $m$, $b$ as a size $m$ x $1$ vector, and the initial $x_{0}$ as a zero vector of size $m$ x $1$. In term of accuracy, we chose a tolerance of $10^{-15}$, and allowed the iterative 1000 iterations to achieve this accuracy.

     With our chosen $x_{0}$, Richardson iteration failed to converge, and partially diverged from the expected solution as it is shown up. Unfortunately we were able to chose an optimal $x_{0}$ which would lead to Richardson iteration convering to $\text{xf}$.

     Jacobi iterative scheme is constructed when $\text{M}$ is chosen to be the diagonal element of matrix $\text{A}$, and is thus denoted as $\text{D}$, e.g., $\text{diag(A)}$. The following is how to derive the Jacobi iterative:

$$Ax=b \to (M-N)x=b \to Mx=Nx+b \to Mx^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b$$

$$\to Dx^{(k+1)}=(D-A)x^{(k)}+b \to D^{-1}Dx^{(k+1)}=D^{-1}(D-A)x^{(k)}+D^{-1}b \to x^{(k+1)}=(I-D^{-1}A)x^{(k)}+D^{-1}b$$

$$\to x^{(k+1)}=x^{(k)}-D^{-1}Ax^{(k)}+D^{-1}b \to x^{(k+1)}=x^{(k)}+D^{-1}b-D^{-1}Ax^{(k)} \to x^{(k+1)}=x^{(k)}+D^{-1}(b-Ax^{(k)})$$

$$\to x^{(k+1)}=x^{(k)}+D^{-1}r^{k}$$

Convergence of Jacobi method is dependent upon the magnitude of the diagonal elements of matrix $\text{A}$, the large these diagonal elements the faster the convergence rate of Jacobi method. Nevertheless we developed a python function named, Jacobi, for the Jacobi iterative scheme.

In [106]:
def Jacobi(A):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    D=np.diag(np.diag(A));

    for i in range(iterMax):
        r=b-A@x;
        x=x+np.linalg.solve(D,r);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     To test the Jacobi iterative scheme, we chose to utilize the same construction that was provided for the test of Richardson iteration. Though to reiterate the terms of accuracy, we chose a tolerance of $10^{-15}$, and allowed the Jacobi iterative 1000 iterations to achieve this degree of accuracy.

     Forward Gauss-seidel is contructed when matrix $\text{M}$ is chosen as the lower triangular of matrix $\text{A}$ including the diagonal elements denoted as $\text{D}$. In simple terms, $\text{M}=\text{tril(A)}=\text{D}-\text{E}$, where matrix $\text{F}$ represents the upper triangular region of matrix $\text{A}$, minus the diagonal elements.

$$Ax=b \to (M-N)x=b \to Mx=Nx+b \to Mx^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b$$

$$\to (D-E)x^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b \to (D-E)x^{(k+1)}=Fx^{(k)}+b.$$

We created a python function named $\text{Foward_GS()}$ for the Forward Gauss-Seidel iterative scheme, we parsed matrix $\text{A}$ into lower triangular matrix $\text{S}$, which includes the diagonal elements denoted in $\text{A}$, and an upper triangular matrix $\text{T}$.

In [110]:
def Foward_GS(A):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    S=np.tril(A);
    T=S-A;

    for i in range(iterMax):
        r=b+T@x;
        x=np.linalg.solve(S,r);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     To test the Forward Gauss-Seidel scheme, we chose to utilize the same construction that was provided for the test of Richardson and Jacobi iterations. Though to reiterate the terms of accuracy, we chose a tolerance of $10^{-15}$, and allowed the Jacobi iterative 1000 iterations to achieve this degree of accuracy.

     Backward Gauss-seidel is contructed when matrix $\text{M}$ is chosen as the upper triangular of matrix $\text{A}$ including the diagonal elements denoted as $\text{D}$. In simple terms, $\text{M}=\text{triu(A)}=\text{D}-\text{F}$, where matrix $\text{E}$ represents the lower triangular region of matrix $\text{A}$, minus the diagonal elements.

$$Ax=b \to (M-N)x=b \to Mx=Nx+b \to Mx^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b$$

$$\to (D-F)x^{(k+1)}=(M-A)x^{(k)}+b \to (D-E)x^{(k+1)}=Ex^{(k)}+b.$$

We created a python function named $\text{Backward_GS()}$ for the Backward Gauss-Seidel iterative scheme, we parsed matrix $\text{A}$ into upper triangular matrix $\text{T}$, which includes the diagonal elements denoted in $\text{A}$, and an lower triangular matrix $\text{S}$.

def Backward_GS(A):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A*x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    D=np.diag(np.diag(A));
    T=np.triu(A);
    S=T-A;

    for i in range(iterMax):
        r=b+S@x;
        x=np.linalg.solve(T,r);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
        
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     Symmetric Gauss-seidel is departure from the previous to scheme, instead of choosing a single matrix $\text{M}$, we parse the iteration itself between Forward Gauss-Seidel and Backward Gauss-Seidel and form a whole iteration through these two schemes.

$$(D-E)x^{(k+1/2)}=Fx^{(k)}+b$$

$$(D-F)x^{(k+1)}=Ex^{(k+1/2)}+b$$

We created a python function named $\text{Symmetric_GS()}$ for the Symmetric Gauss-Seidel iterative scheme, we incorportated the parsed matrice from Forward Gauss-Seidel and Backward Gauss-Seidel. In other words, $\text{A}$ was parsed into lower triangular matrix $\text{S}$ which includes the diagonal elements found in $\text{D}$, and upper triangular matrix $\text{T}$. Also matrix $\text{A}$ was parsed into upper triangular matrix $\text{F}$ which also contains the diagonal elements fround in matrix $\text{D}$, and lower triangular matrix $\text{S}$. Following for each scheme we calculate the residual, then implicitly calculating the inverse of matrix $\text{M}$ in each portion of the parsed iteration.

In [118]:
def Symmetrix_GS(A):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    D=np.diag(np.diag(A));
    S=np.tril(A);
    T=S-A;

    F=np.triu(A);
    E=F-A;

    for i in range(iterMax):
        r=b+T@x;
        x=np.linalg.solve(S,r);
        s=b+E@x;
        x=np.linalg.solve(F,s);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     A variation of Gauss-Seidel, successive over-relation (SOR) is an iterative scheme meant to attain a faster convergence rate than normal Gauss-seidel, while possessing applicability to solve less than optimitally conditioned matrices. In consequence Forward SOR is derived in similar fashion to Gauss-Seidel, though the parsing of matrix $\text{A}$ is quite different.

$$\omega A = \omega (D-E-F)=(D-\omega E)-(\omega F + (1+\omega)D) = M - N$$

When $\omega = 1$, the this iterative scheme become the normal Gauss-seidel iterative scheme, but when $\omega$ is between $0 < \omega > 1$ the iterative scheme becomes relaxed, while when $\omega$ is between $1 < \omega < 2$ the iterative scheme become over-relaxed. In conception the practitioner tries to fit an optimal $\omega$ to the iterative scheme to cause of relaxation or over-relaxation in the system, so that the scheme can achieve a faster convergence rate than Gauss-Seidel. Though similarly Gauss-Seidel, successive over-relaxation requires that the matrix $\text{A}$ possess only real eigenvalues and a spectral radius below 1 for the SOR iterative scheme to converge.

     In the same fashion as the previous algorithms, we created an python function named in the name of the iterative scheme, as such, we composed $\text{Forward_SOR()}$ and named it as such.

     Backward successive over-relaxation (SOR) is paradigm of the SOR and Backward Gauss-Seidel, where the parsing of matrix $\text{A}$ is in similar fashion to Backward Gauss-Seidel - though the parsement are perturbed by an omega parameter, $\omega$, which deviate the scheme slightly.

$$\omega A = \omega (D-E-F)=(D-\omega F-(\omega E+ (1+\omega)D) = M - N$$

Which practically make the scheme almost identical to Forward SOR, except the backward system is solving the upper triangular matrix $\text{T}$ instead of the lower triangular matrix $\text{S}$.

     Nonetheless we composed an python function named, $\text{Backward_SOR()}$ with the slight modification to the algorithm which transform the scheme from Forward to Backward.

In [127]:
def Backward_SOR(A,w):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    D=np.diag(np.diag(A));
    T=np.triu(A);

    for i in range(iterMax):
        r=b-A@x;
        x=x+np.linalg.solve(T,r);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

     To test the Backward SOR scheme, we yet again chose to utilize the same construction that was utilized in previous tests, though we included an $\omega$ parameter denoted as $\text{w}$ in the code, as the perturbation parameter to the system.

     Symmetric SOR is a paradigm of Symmetric Gauss-seidel, though of course there exists an omega, $\omega$ which perturbates the parsed matrices of matrix $\text{A}$. Yet again due to the paradigm relationship between the two iterative schemes, after a derivation to form Forward SOR and Backward SOR, we attain a similar parsed iterative structure to Symmetric Gauss-Seidel.

$$(D-\omega E)x^{(k+1/2)}=(\omega F+ (1-\omega)D)x^{(k)}+\omega b$$

$$(D-\omega F)x^{(k+1)}=(\omega E+(1-\omega)D)x^{(k+1/2)}+\omega b$$

We composed symmetric SOR, and named it $\text{symmetric_SOR}$.

In [131]:
def Symmetric_SOR(A,w):
    iteration=0;
    r=b-A@x0;
    r0=LA.norm(r);
    error_vec=np.zeros(iterMax);
    error=r0;
    x=x0;
    xf=np.linalg.solve(A,b);
    Error=np.zeros(iterMax);

    D=np.diag(np.diag(A));
    S=np.tril(A);
    S=S-D; S=(w)*S; S=S+D;
    F=np.triu(A); F=(w)*F; F=F+D;

    for i in range(iterMax):
        iteration = iteration + 1;
        r=b-A@x;
        x=x+np.linalg.solve(S,r);
        s=b-A@x;
        x=x+np.linalg.solve(F,s);
        error_vec[i]=LA.norm(r);
        error=LA.norm(r);
        Error[i]=np.abs(LA.norm(xf-x));
        print("Error =" + " " + str(Error[i]))
    
        if Error[i] < tol:
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
            
    return x,Error,error,xf;

C.4 (30 points) Implement the one-dimensional projection methods: Steepest decent, Residual norm steepest descent, and Minimy Residual iteration.

     Solution:

     The last objective for this project is to implement non-stationary iterative methods, also known as projection methods, as each of these scheme utlizes a non-orthogonal projection method to attain the solution of a linear system. The first of the projection methods will be Steepest Descent, like the others, a one-dimensional projection method with $K=L=\text{span}\{r\}$, which is the span of the residual provide by $r=b-Ax$ of the iterative's current iteration. For this projection scheme to converge it requires matrix $A$ to be symmetric positive definite (e.g. SPD), otherwise the project scheme will most probably diverge while iterating.

     Instead of developing our own algorithm to Steepest Descent, we borrowed $\text{mysteepest()}$ written in MATLAB from Dr. Michael Rozman of the University of Connecticut, the source code can be found in a document that can be found here . Nevertheless we translate the MATLAB into Python, and named the python function $\text{Steepest_Descent()}$.

In [198]:
def Steepest_Descent(A,b,x,tol):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x;
    delta=np.transpose(r)@r;
    converg=delta;
    delta0=delta;
    
    conv=np.zeros(iterMax);
    deltal=np.zeros(iterMax)
    
    for i in range(iterMax):
        q=A@r;
        alpha=delta/(np.transpose(q)@r);
        x=x+alpha*r;
        if np.remainder(i,50)==0:
            r=b-A@x;
        else:
            r=r-alpha*q;
            
        delta=np.transpose(r)@r;
        conv[i]=converg;
        deltal[i]=delta;
        print("convergence =" + " " + str(deltal[i]))
        
        if delta < (tol*delta0):
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
    
    return x,conv;

     To test $\text{Steepest_Descent()}$, we generated a symmetric positive definite matrix $\text{A}$ through our function, $\text{diagonally_dominant_matrix()}$. We then generated a solution vector $\text{b}$ of size $m$ x $1$, and an initial $x$ vector of the same size as $b$. In regards to accuracy and max iteration, we chose a tolerence of $10^{-15}$ and a max iteration of 1000.

def SPD(n,m):
    a=n; b=m;
    A=np.random.random((a,b))
    n=A.shape[0];
    A=0.5*(A+np.transpose(A));
    A=A+10*np.eye(n);
    
    return A;

def Residual_Norm_Steepest_Descent(A,b,x,tol):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x;
    
    for i in range(iterMax):
        v=np.transpose(A)@r;
        q=A@v;
        delta=np.transpose(v)@v;
        
        if i==0:
            delta0=delta;

        alpha=delta/(np.transpose(q)@q);
        x=x+alpha*v;
        if np.remainder(i,50)==0:
            r=b-A@x;
        else:
            r=r-alpha*q;
            
        delta=np.transpose(v)@v;
        conv=converg;
        deltal=delta;
        print("convergence =" + " " + str(deltal))
        
        if delta < (tol*delta0):
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
    
    return x,converg;

     The third and last projection method that we will implement will be Minimal Residual iteration for a SPD matrix $\text{A}$. MRI method is an one-dimensional projection method with $k=\text{span}\{r\}$, $L=Ak$, where the residual vector is attained from the residual formula, $r=b-Ax$, the residual vector is representative measure of residue of the ith iteration, aka of the then current iteration. Nonetheless we extrapolated the development of coding of this python function from $\text{Steepest Descent()}$.

In [304]:
def Minimal_residual_iteration(A,b,x,tol):
    iterMax=1000;
    r=b-A@x;
    
    for i in range(iterMax):
        q=A@r;
        delta=np.transpose(q)@r;
        
        if i==0:
            delta0=delta;
        
        alpha=delta/(np.transpose(q)@q);
        x=x+alpha*r;
        if np.remainder(i,50)==0:
            r=b-A@x;
        else:
            r=r-alpha*q;
            
        delta=np.transpose(q)@r;
        conv=converg;
        deltal=delta;
        print("convergence =" + " " + str(deltal))
        
        if delta < (tol*delta0):
            print("iteration =" + " " + str(i))
            break;
    
    return x,converg;

     To test $\text{ Minimal_residual_iteration()}$, we generated a symmetric positive definite matrix $\text{A}$ through our function, $\text{SPD()}$. We then generated a solution vector $\text{b}$ of size $m$ x $1$, and an initial $x$ vector of the same size as $b$. In regards to accuracy and max iteration, we chose a tolerence of $10^{-15}$ and a max iteration of 1000.
